## Adding or Modifying Skills

1. Create `skills/<skill-name>/SKILL.md` with required frontmatter (`name:`, `description:`, `version:`, `benchmark:` — see Benchmark mandate below).
2. Update `MANIFEST.md`: bump version, update description.
3. Update `SKILL.md` frontmatter version to match.
4. Add a row to the skill's `tests/benchmark.md` (or create it from `templates/benchmark.md.tmpl`) recording the version's measured improvement metric.
5. Commit changes together.
6. Run `bash scripts/instructions_on_start.sh` to verify integrity check passes.

**Repo vs. global skills:**
- `skills/` — marketplace skills, versioned, used by downstream consumers. Commit here.
- `~/.claude/skills/gsd-*` — GSD meta-framework skills, installed globally by Claude Code. NOT part of this repo.
- `speckit-*` — DomI-origin only. Not available in downstream sessions until synced. Do NOT assume `/speckit.*` commands work in consumer repos without first running `claude plugin install sync-from-domi@DomI && /sync from DomI`. See issue #54.

**Consolidation policy (ratified per #52, 2026-05-18):** keep skills granular. Hooks already handle de-facto consolidation of cross-cutting infra (see `MANIFEST.md ### Hooks`). Do NOT merge existing skills without operator sign-off; merges risk breaking caller chains, explicitly scoped out by the operator. Re-evaluate when per-session skill-invocation telemetry exists.

### Benchmark mandate (per #21, 2026-05-18)

Every skill `SKILL.md` MUST declare a `benchmark:` frontmatter field naming the metric it improves across versions. Examples:

| Skill | benchmark |
|---|---|
| `git-push-fallback` | `wasted_tool_calls_on_push_failure` |
| `check-done` | `seconds_to_dedup_detection` |
| `verify-plan` | `false_pass_rate_on_underspec_issues` |
| `dispatch-issue` | `mean_session_minutes_per_issue` |

Each version bump in `MANIFEST.md` must be accompanied by a row in `skills/<name>/tests/benchmark.md` (template: `templates/benchmark.md.tmpl`) recording:

```
| version | date | metric | baseline | observed | delta | evidence |
```

Versions without a measured delta land as `not-measured`, flagged on the next session-start integrity check. This is how we resist skill bloat without manual review — every version must justify itself with a number. Closes #21.

**Rollout status (#76)**: Phase 1 — 5 highest-frequency skills backfilled (2026-05-19). Phase 2a — `scripts/instructions_on_start.sh` benchmark check live at warning level (one `⚠` line per missing skill, ISSUES bucket only — never BLOCKED). Disable per-session with `BENCHMARK_CHECK_SKIP=1`. Phase 2b (2026-05-20) — 10 cross-repo high-traffic skills backfilled (bootstrap-vm, list-issues, dispatch-wave, log-issue, merge-guard, send-email, enforce-branch-policy, gh-issues, github-release, doc-issue); missing-count 55 → 45. Phase 2c (2026-05-20) — 10 more skills backfilled across two passes (validate-imports, skill-issue-closure, show-image, api-key-rotation, git-issue-label-manager, then act-autonomously, pypi-publish, digest, health-checkin, wealth-checkin); missing-count 47 → 37. Phase 2d (2026-05-20) — speckit-* family (15 skills) backfilled with shared metric `validation_failures_per_100_invocations`; missing-count 37 → 22. Phase 2d-continued (2026-05-20) — 2 first-class DomI contract plugins backfilled (`sync-from-domi`, `request-from-domi`); missing-count 22 → 20. `mcp-binary-push` (DomI #85) ships with benchmark in the same release, so the new-skill add does not increment the warning. Phase 2e (2026-05-20) — bootstrap output split into first-party (Phase 3 ratchet, ticks ISSUES) vs. vendored-upstream (informational `ⓘ`, does not tick ISSUES). Vendored prefix registry lives at `scripts/vendored_skills.txt`. Status today: first-party at zero (`✓ Phase 3 ratchet at zero`), vendored at 20. Phase 3 — promote to BLOCKER after 2-week grace window (target ~2026-06-02); the BLOCK promotion gates on first-party=0, which is already true. All skill PRs landing in the window must ship with `benchmark:` + tracker. Remaining 20 vendored (hf-* 13, caveman/* 5, grill-me + grill-with-docs 2) stay deferred pending operator vendor-vs-fork decision; promotion to first-party (e.g. after a fork) is a one-line removal from `scripts/vendored_skills.txt`.

